Analysis of How to Find the Best Players in Fantasy Football¶

Authored by Ryan Lott¶

Introduction¶

Football season is among us. Many fans of the NFL play a game each year called fantasy football. This game consists of drafting real NFL players with your friends and creating you're own "fantasy team". Your team does well based on how you're players do in real life. Picking the best players can be contributed to many factors such as playing with other good players, having a good offensive, and having a good defense among other factors as well. Throughout this prject we will look at these different factors to try and determine which one can correlate to a higher scoring player.

For this project all data will be pulled from the Pro Football Focus website. We are going to use data from the years 2018-2022 form these categories: - Quarterbacks - Running Backs - Wide Receivers & Tight Ends - Offensive Lines

Using this data we will be able find expectations for how well an NFL player should perform based an certain statistics.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now that we have all of our data we can start making transformations and visualizing some relationships. First to make sure our data is consistent we need to add a fantasy points per game column to the tables that do not already have it. Players can miss games for many reasons like an injury, illness, or even for having covid symptoms in some recent years. To standardize these discrepancies will calculate each players fantasy points per game in a column called 'fantasyPpg' and also sort by this new column

In [17]:
def calcPointsPerGameAndSort(df):
    df['fantasyPpg'] = df['fantasyPts'] / df['games']
    df.sort_values('fantasyPpg', ascending=False, inplace=True)
    df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    return df
In [18]:
for df in quarterback_data:
    calcPointsPerGameAndSort(df)
for df in runningback_data:
    calcPointsPerGameAndSort(df)
for df in passcatcher_data:
    calcPointsPerGameAndSort(df)

The plots above show the relationship between a teams top pass catcher in fantasy points per game in relation to their quarterbacks fantasy points per game. The red lines represent the data's line of best fit and as you can see generally the the more points a quartback scores the more points their pass catchers will score. Now we will look at if the same holds true for the quarterback to runningback relationship.

Models¶

Now that we have seen how different statistical categories can affect a positions fantasy production. We are going to look at a full ordinary least squares regression model. This will allow us to make predictions on fantasy production based on the given stats and we will be able to see which stats have strong correlations.

The first model we are going to look at is how can a quarterbacks production predict a wide receivers production.

In [53]:
qb_to_pc_full = pd.concat([qb_to_pc_2018, qb_to_pc_2019, qb_to_pc_2020, qb_to_pc_2021, qb_to_pc_2022])
In [54]:
pass_catcher_model = smf.ols(formula='fantasyPpg_y ~ fantasyPpg_x', data=qb_to_pc_full).fit()
In [55]:
pass_catcher_model.summary()

m = pass_catcher_model.params['fantasyPpg_x']
b = pass_catcher_model.params['Intercept']
x_values = np.array([10.0, 27.5])
In [57]:

plt.xlabel("Quarterback PPG")
plt.ylabel("Running Back PPG")
plt.title("2018-2022 Quarterback PPG vs Running Back PPG")
plt.show()

The model above shows the ordinary least squares regression for the relationship between a quarterbacks fantasy production and the teams top wide recevier production. With this model we could predict relatively how well we can expect a teams top wide receiver to do based on their quarterback. For the NFL season this year for example I expect a receiver like Chris Olave who plays for the New Orleans Saints to take a jump in fantasy production since his quarterback has improved from Andy Dalton to Derek Carr. An example of a receiver whose production I would expect to go down is Mike Evans of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers since his quarterback has regressed from Tom Brady to Baker Mayfield. Since the p-value of the coefficients in the model above are less than 0.05 we can reject the null hypothesis of no relationship between a quarterback's fantasy ppg and their top pass catcher's fantasy ppg. This allows us to conclude that there is a correlation between these statistics as well.

The model above shows the ordinary least squares regression for the relationship between a quarterbacks fantasy production, and the teams top running back's targets and production. With this model we could predict relatively how well we can expect a teams top running back to do based on their quarterback and targets that they get in the passing game. For the NFL season this year for example I expect a receiver like Alvin Kamara who plays for the New Orleans Saints to take a jump in fantasy production since his quarterback has improved and he plays in a system that targets running backs in the pass game. An example of a running back whose production I would expect to go down is Josh Jacobs of the Las Vegas Raiders since his quarterback has regressed and his new quarterback does not have a history of throwing to the running back much in the pass game. Since the p-value of the coefficients in the running back model above are less than 0.05 we can reject the null hypothesis of no relationship between a running back's production and their targets along with their quarterbacks production. Again this allows us to conclude that there is a correlation between these statistics.

Conclusions¶

As we can see from the data above we can make some good predictions about how a football players will perform in fantasy points this upcoming season. Through regression analysis, visualization and hypothesis testing we were able to draw the conclusions that a pass catcher will have good fantasy football production this NFL season if they have a good quarterback throwing them the ball. If a wide recevier switched teams this offseason and their quarterback has improved we can expect their fantasy production to go up, and vice versa if a pass catcher switched teams to a worse quarterback. When looking at rookie pass catchers this year we can expect the receivers that went to teams with a good quarterback to have better production. In addition to that we can make the conclusion that a running back will be likely to have a better fantasy season if again they have a good quarterback that includes them more in the passing game. Having a good quarterback allows for more opportunities for the running back to get carries and allows for more scoring opportunities. Involving them in the passsing game makes them more dynamic and more difficult to stop on defense. We can expect a rookie like Jahmyr Gibbs to have a good seasom given he has a relatively good quarterback and has good pass catching skills. Finally we can come to the conclusion that a quarterback will have a good fantasy season if they have a good offensive line in front of them and they have good running ability. If a quarterback goes to a new team with a better offensive line or better offensive linemen are brought into their team we can expect their fantasy production to increase and vice versa if they have a worse offensive line. Out of all the rookie quarterbacks this year I expect Anthony Richardson to have the best fantasy season given that he has an average offensive line and has great running ability, along with an offensive system that will give him plenty of rushing opportunities. I will use these conclusions in my leagues this year and expect to perform very well and hopefully win some leagues.
